Debt Yields vs. Returns
Yield to maturity of a bond = IRR the bond investor will earn
from holding the bond to maturity (Chapter 6)
If default risk is low, we can just use the YTM as an estimate of
investors expected return
However, if default risk is significant, the YTM (promised
return) will overstate investors expected return
Debt Yields vs. Returns
Consider a one-year bond with YTM of y
For each $1 invested, the bond promises to pay $(1+y) in one
year
The bond will default with probability p, in which case bond
holders will receive only $(1+y-L)
L is the expected loss per $1 of debt in the event of default
Debt Yields vs. Returns
With the assumptions, the expected return of the bond is
rd= (1-p)y + p(y-L) = y pL
= Yield to Maturity Prob(default)*Expected Loss Rate
The importance of these adjustments will depend on the
riskiness of the bond
The average loss rate for unsecured debt is about 60%
Debt Yields vs. Returns
For a B-rated bond, the expected return to debt holders would
be approximately 3.3% (0.055*0.60) below the bonds quoted
yield
Debt Betas
Can be estimated in the same was as equity betas, using
historical returns (individual return data for may be hard to
obtain)
We can also approximate beta using estimates of betas of
bond indices by rating category
For equity or debt, we estimate the cost of capital from
historical data
When considering a new project, this approach is not
feasible
The most common method for estimating a projects beta is
from comparable firms in the same line of business as the
project
All-Equity Comparables
The simplest setting is when we can find an all-equity
financed firm in a single line of business that is comparable to
the new possible project
If the firms average investment has similar market risk to the
project, the comparable firms equity beta and cost of capital
can be used
Levered Firms as Comparables
It is not always possible to find an all-equity comparable firm
If the comparable firm has debt, its cash flows will be used to
pay both debt and equity holders
Thus the cost of equity are not representative because the
firm is levered, the equity will often be much riskier
Levered Firms as Comparables
For a levered firm, we can recreate a claim on the firms assets
by holding both its debt and equity
The return and beta of the firm will be equal to those of the
combined debt and equity portfolio
